oc:kn_01138022 a oc:Heuristic,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When deciding between 2×2 matrix and other visualization types in Step 5" ;
    oc:directiveContent "2×2 matrices work best when two dominant competitive factors define the landscape; use radar/spider charts for multi-factor comparison when no two factors dominate" ;
    oc:hasRationale "The matrix format forces clarity by reducing complexity to two axes, but only when two factors truly capture the competitive dynamics" .

oc:kn_70690a1a a oc:DesignPrinciple,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "When building Step 5 positioning visualization and choosing a 2×2 matrix format" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Use industry-specific axis pairs for 2×2 positioning matrices: Technology/SaaS → Product breadth × Customer segment or Integration depth × Geographic reach; Consumer/Retail → Price point × Product range or Online × Offline presence; Financial Services → Product complexity × Customer sophistication or Scale × Specialization; Healthcare → Care setting × Payer mix or Technology enablement × Service breadth; Industrial → Customization × Scale or Geographic scope × Vertical focus." ;
    oc:hasRationale "Industry-standard axis pairs produce more insightful positioning maps because they reflect the competitive dimensions that actually drive differentiation in that sector" .

oc:kn_7da6ff78 a oc:Constraint,
        oc:KnowledgeNode ;
    oc:appliesToContext "Before creating any positioning visualization" ;
    oc:directiveContent "Axis pair selection should be confirmed with the user via ask_user_question before building the visualization, as the choice of axes shapes the entire strategic narrative" ;
    oc:hasRationale "Different axis pairs tell different competitive stories; the user's strategic intent should drive the choice, not the analyst's assumption" .

